This is a Pyramid Lake strain Lahontan cutthroat trout.  This strain was thought to be extinct when dams and water diversions blocked their spawning areas. The strain was rediscovered when Nevada Department of Wildlife was surveying streams in eastern Nevada where they weren’t expected to be. Apparently someone stocked these fish in the stream at some point before they disappeared from Pyramid Lake and the Truckee River. The fish have been reestablished and are now caught regularly by anglers. Historically, these cutthroat reached enormous sizes. The world record is 42lbs and there were rumors of 100lb fish when there was a commercial fishery.
